{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_adamsmorgan_ver01/data/sn84026749/0022225467A/1930011001/0213.xml":{"full_text":"REPORT SHOWS\nBUSBUSINESS\nPITS MOST\nBus operation is the most prof\nitable branch of the Capital Trac\ntion Company\u2019s business, accord\ning to figures included in Presi\ndent John Hanna\u2019s report for\n1929 at the corporation s annual\nmeeting yesterday.-\nHanrtl reported that bus pas\nsenger revenues for 1929 were\n14.689.28 more than tor the pre\nvious year and that revenue de\nrived from Special bus chartering\nlast year exceeded the previous\nyear\u2019s revenue from the same\nsource by $52,640.36.\nHanna was re-elected president\nas were the following other offi\ncers: George E. Hamilton, chair\nman of the board;; H D. Cramp\nton, vice president, secretary and\ntreasurer; John Fleming, assistant\ntreasurer, and C. B. Koontz, as\nsistant treasurer.\nThe following were re-elected as\nmembers of the board of direc\ntors: George E. Hamilton, Ed\nward J. Stellwagen, John F. Lar\ncombe, John M. Perry, John H.\nHanna, Charles C. Glover, Jr\u201e and\nG. Thomas Dunlop.\nThe annual report covering the\nyear\u2019s activities in street railway\nand bus line operations showed;\nPassenger revenues for the\nyear amounted to $3,937,171.44, a\ndecrease over 1928 of $104,307.55.\nBus passenger revenues totaled\n$247,670.33 in 1929. an Increase\nover the 1928 total of $4,689.23.\nSpecial bus revenues amounted\nto $73,059.43, an increase during\nthe year of $52,604.36.\nTotal revenues from transpor\ntation amounted to $4,257,901.26,\na- decrease of over $47,000 from\nlast year. Revenues from opera\ntions other than transportation\nshowed a slight falling off.\nNet operating revenues of the\nCapital Traction Co. for the year\nreached the sum of $1,229,534.00,\na decrease over the previous year\nOs $49,632.37.\nTaxes assignable to transporta\ntion operations totaled $327,-\n691.94, a decrease of $19,373.38.\nGross income for the y-ar\namounted to $928,811.63, a slump\nover 1928 of $45,313.98.\nAfter all deductions from gross\nIncome, ampunting to over $366,-\n000, the company had a total net\nincome of $561,974.43, a decline\nof $58,431.17.\nThe credit balance at the close\nof the year was $759,592.96, ir a\ndecrease compared with 1928 of\n$248,534.63.\nSGHrOLES\nINCREASE\nNEW YORK.Jan. 10.\u2014Reporting\nconsolidated gross sales of $19,-\n054,101 for 1929, Schulte-United\n6c to ~\u00a3l.OO Stores, Inc., which\nbegan operations a little more\nthan a year ago, achieved a place\namong the 10 largest chain store i\ncompanies engaged in similar\nbusiness.\nSales for December, 1929, totaled\n$3,911,050, compared with $1,500,-\n483 for December, 1928. which\nmarked the company\u2019s first full\nmonth of operation. Based on\nmonthly sales for December, the\ncompany ranks seventh in size\namong the junior department\nstore chains.\nRapid expansion during 1929,!\nbrought the number of stores in\noperation at the end of the year\nto 111.\nLivestock Marts\nCHICAGO\nCHICAGO, Jan. 10.\u2014Ilogs\u2014Receipts,\n*8,000; market 10-15 c lower. Top, $10;\nSulk, $9.5009.90; heavy weight. |9.35\u00ae\nSVI; medium weight. $9.60\u00ae 10; light\n_ height, $9.700 10; light lights, $965\u00ae\nK; packing aowa, $8,250 9; pigs, $9.10\n9.90. Holdovers, 10,000.\nCattle \u2014Receipts, 2,000; market steady.\nHalves \u2014Receipts, 1,000; market steady.\nBeet steers\u2014Good and choice, sl3\u00ae\nKS.CO: common and medium, $10013;\nyearlings, slo\u00ae 18.60. Butcher cattle\u2014\nHelfers. s\u00df\u00a9ls; cows, $6.25011.50;\nFulls, $8011; calves, $13016.60; feeder\nbteers, $8.50 011; stocker steers, SBO\n10.50; Stocker cows and heifers, $609.50.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 9,000; market steady,\ngfedlum and choice lambs. 513.50@14.50;\nbulls and common, $10012; yearlings,\nI1O01S.6O; common and choice ewes,\n14*7.50; feeder lambs, sll @l3.\nBALTIMORE\n\nBALTIMORE, Jan. 9. \u2014Livestock\u2014\nCattla\u2014 Receipts, 100 head; light sup\nply, market steady. Steers, good to\nloice, *12.75013; medium to good.\n1.50012.50; fair to medium. $10,250\n.*5; plain to fair. $9.25010.25; com\n>n to plain. $8.2509.25; bulls, good\nchoice, *009.50; medium to good.\n7*ot.7R: fair to medium. *7 07.50:\ntin to fair, *6 07; common to plain.\n06; cows, good to choice. $8 08.50;\n\u00bbdlum to good, *7 07.75; fair to me\num. *6.2506.75: plain to fair. *506:\ntpmon to plain. *304.50; heifers, good\nchoice. *10011; medium to good.\n010; fair to medium. *809; plain\nfair. *7OS; common .to plain. S6O\nfresh cows and apringera, *600150.\nSheep \u00abnd lambs, receipts. 100 head\nlight supply; market steady; sheep. *2\nlambs. *6.50015.\nNEW YORK\nNEW YORK, Jan.\ncattle \u2014Market receipts none; direct,\n<OOO head; no cattle on sale, prices\nFere nominal.\nVpalers and Calves\u2014Market receipts,\ng\u00abo head: no cattle on sale: prices\nBCaree,. steady, mostly of New York\narlytn. Good to choice, *16018;\nbnedium,- *11015; cull and common\n**olo. No ealves on aale.\nHogs\u2014Market receipts none: directs, I\nr\u00ae. head. None offered.\nSheep\u2014Market receipts, no head;!\ndirects, >,980 head; lambs scarce, steady.\nOdd head goo<9 to choice, $14.50;\nmedium *12011.50. few commoi $9.\nNEW YORK CURB MARKET H\n(Furnished bv W. B. Hibbs A\nHaags Belos\u2014 Net\n1920 Name Add 00 High Low 13:15 Ch ge\n10% 10 Aero Supply 8..-\u2022 2 10 10 10\n15% 13% Aero Underwear.. 1 154> 15% 15'4+,\n24 23% Afgf An 2 22% 22% 22%\n41% 35% Allied PAU S 39% 39% 39%\n*i Ji Allison Drug A... 1\nJi Allison Drug 8... 1 Ji Ji Vi\n108% 107*4 Alum Co of Am pf 1 ICB 108 108 Ji\n5 Am Brit A Cont... 8 5 5 5\n41% 40% American Chain-. 8 41Ji 41% 41%+ Ji\n39 38% Am Cities How A. 2\u00a39 39 39\n16H 14 Am Cities Pow B. 3 16V, 16% 16%\n.5 23'., AmComnw A.*--. 8 24 24 24 Ji\n28 J .6 Am Cyan B 3 \u2019.7% 16% \u00a36Ji- Ji\n5 3Ji Am Dept Store--.. 3 3% 3% 3%\n18 1 \u201eAm Equities...... 5 18 18 18 41%\n75 65% Am FPw ww 5 74 73 s 73%+ Ji\n11H 104. Am ins inc 8.... 7 10 1