day\u2019s close.\nUnited States Steel and Beth\nlehem forged ahead behind a\nstrong buying demand, accom\npanying the reports of higher\noperations in the mill* of these\ngiant corporations. From a low\nof 45 per cent of capacity opera\ntions in last December, Bethlehem,\nhas expanded to 71 per cent of\nmill capacity and United States\nSteel mills are now functioning\n65 per cent of capacity, according\nto reports received today. This\nis the most favorable news of the\nbusiness revival since the break\nIn the market last October.\nBethlehem sold up to 97\u2019/ 2 for\na new gain of 2% points and a\nrecovery of 11*4 points from the\nm <rf i week United States\n?l eel a x 173 \u2019howed a recovery of\n15 points by the later comparison.\nCentral Alloy Steel, Vanadium\nand Crucible rose about a point\neach.\njnie utilities sold at slightly\nhigher price levels than in yes\nterday\u2019s market, but new ad-\nX? nces were comparatively smaH.\nThe coppers and motors were\nunder profit-taking -and the oils\nslumped off on the renewed price\ncutting in the industry.\nGold Dust continued its confi\ndent upward move and reached a\nnew high at 42\u20194.\nCall money was unchanged at\n54 per cent.\nConnecticut Planes\nTo Be Greeted Here\nPassengers in four airplanes of\nthe Connecticut National Guard\nenroute to the All-American Air\nRaces at Miami will make a short\nstop here and be greeted at 11:30\na. m. at Bolling Field by repre\nsentatives of the Washington\nChamber of Commerce.\nThe representatives of the\nChamber, headed by Creed W.\nFulton, vice chairman of the\naviation committee, include Clif\nton Aires, William M. Aitchison,\nGranville Gude, George B.\nKeneipp, T. S. Settle. William O.\nTufts, W. W. Wheeler and Dorsey\nW. Hyde, Jr.\nGrain Markets\nBALTIMORE\nBALTIMORE, Jan. B.\u2014Wheat Easier;\nNo. 2, red winter spot, 81.29%; No.\n1 red winter garlicky spot, domestic,\n81.26%. Receipt., 1.487 bushel; ship\nments. 1t.<44 bushel*\nCorn\u2014Steady; No. 1 yellow, domestic,\ncariota new, 81.05 buahel; receipts.\n4,903 bushel.; shipments. 711 bushels.\nOats\u2014Dull; supply ample; No. 2\nwhite domestic carlots, 55c bushel; No.\n3, white, 54c bushel. Shipments. 1,541\nbushels.\nRye\u2014Nominal: shipments 34 bushels.\nHay\u2014Firm; demand eaual to offer\ning of good hay.\nFlour\u2014Quiet.\nCHICAGO\nCHICAGO. Jan 9 (I.N.S.).\u2014Cash\nGrain dose:\nWheat\u2014No. hard, 81.24%; No. 5\nmixed. $1.13; No. 3 hard yellow, 31.22%.\nCorn\u2014No. 4 mixed. 83c; No. 5 mixed,\n81982 c; No. mixed. 78\u00a979%c; No. 4\nyellow, 83\u00ae86%c; No. 5 yellow, 81@84c;\nNo. 8 yellow, 79%081c; No. 4 white,\n86\u00ae86%c; No. 5 whits, 81%\u00ae84c;\nsample grade, 46\u00a978c.\nOats\u2014No. 8 white, 44% 046%e; No.\n4 white, 44%045c.\nRye\u2014None. Barley. 43Otte.\nCHICAGO FUTURES\nCHICAGO, Jan. 9 (IHS.)r-\nGrains closed higher today. Wheat\nwas up y 4 c; corn, 1% to l%c and\noats *4 to %c.\nWheat ruled lower during the\nforenoon with general selling on\ndisappointing cables and fairly\nheavy snowfall over the winter\nbelt. Buying power was limited\nand chiefly inspired by strength\nin corn. Liverpool was 8 d lower.\nBuenos Aires opened to 1c\nhigher after closing 2*4c lower yes\nterday. These violent fluctuations\nwere attributed to changes in ex\nchange rates, rather tiityi to direct\nmarket factors.\nCorn was strong with buying on\nthe Government report showing\nthat the 1929 crop harvested for\ngrain aggregated only 2,191,135,-\n000 bushels, or 7 per cent less than\nlast year\u2019s and the smallest since\n1924. Unfavorable weather over\nthe belt which is expected to result\nin lighter receipts, also was a mar\nkeWactor. Offerings were scat-\nOats were higher in sympathy\nwith corn.\nEstimated carlot receipts were:\nWheat, 16; corn, 137, and oats, 2.\n(Furnished by W, B, Hibbs A Co.)\nIQyen |High| Low ICloae\nWheat\u2014 Illi\nMarch 128 128% 127%|128%\nMaj f 131% 132%|130%1132%\nl u \u2019y 131% 133%i131%|133%\n_ Corn\u2014 Illi\nMarch 92 I 93% 9