060 c; jumbo squab* 75081-25.\nPHILADELPHIA\nPHILADELPHIA, Jan. B\u2014Live Poultry\n\u2014Fowls, not leghorn* fancy, 30c; ordi\nnary, 36\u00ae 28c; leghorn fowls, fancy. 25\nO26o; ordinary, 220 24c; spring chick\nens. Plymouth rock* fancy. 17o; ordi\nnary. 24\u00ae 28c; mixed color* fancy. 25\n026 c; ordinary, 22024 c; fancy roasting\nchickens, weighing 5 pounds or over,\n27c: fancy broiler* weighing 1 pounds\nor under, 300*2c; leghorn broiler* soft\nmeated, 24c; staggy young rooster* 28\n024 c; old rooster* 30 0 32c; turkey*\nfancy, 30c; turkey* ordinary, 27029 c;\nold gobbler* 38c: duck* sane/, white\npeking. 38c; mixed color* 22\u00ae23c; mus\ncovy, 15918 c; guineas, young, weigh\ning 2 pounds or over, per pair. 81.30;\nundersized, 81; old, 80c per pair; poor\nstock and cull* lower; geese, fat, 200\n.22c; ordinary, 18019 c; pigeon* per\npair, young, 35c; old, 38040 c.\nDressed Poultry\u2014Quotations: Fowl*\nfresh killed In boxes, 5 pounds or over.\n34c; 4 to 4% pound* 31033 c; 8 to 8%\npound* 28O30e; 3% pound* 35 0 28c,\nunder 2% pound* 22034 c; chicken*\nWestern. In boxe* 6% pounds or over.\n34c; weighing 5 pound* 33c; weighing\n4 to 4% pounds, 30O81e; weighing 3\nto 3% pound* 28G39c; weighing 2%\npound* 29 0 30c; 2 pound* 80O32e;\nweighing 1% pound* 310 340; old roost\ner* dry-picked, Western, 5 pounds or\nover, 25c; under 8 pound* 23024*\nTurkeys, nearby, fancy, 88O40c; fair to\ngood, 35037 c; Western fancy, 87039 c;\npoor to g00d,a84036c; old tom* near\nby, 33038 c; Western, 28 0 30c. Duck*\n22023 c. Gees* 30 023 c.\nButter\u2014Declfted %c. Quotations:\nHigher scoring, 38%039%C; 92 seor*\n35%c; 91 seor* 34%c; 90 score, 230\n33%c; 89 seor* 82o; 88 seor* 30c; 87\nseor* 29 %c; 88 score, 28%c.\nEggs\u2014Advanced 10. Freeh, extr*\nfirst* 49c; first* in new case* 440;\nfirst* in second-hand case* 45%c; sec\nond* 42046 c.\nCheese\u2014Quiet and unchanged. Whole\nmilk, Longhorn* 220<2%c; single dais\nies fresh. 22 0 22%c.\nSEES HAILWS\nUNHURTBY\nPLANES\nBOSTON, Jan. 10\nPresident John J. Pelley of the\nNew. York, New Haven and Hart\nford Railroad told the Bond Chib\nthis afternoon that he saw no\nserious threat to railroads from\ncompetition by water, busses,\nmotor trucks or airplanes.\nHe added that any new devel\nopment of merit will succeed and\ncrush those who oppose it. He\nsaid:\n\u201cI cannot visualise the time\nwhen the railroads will not be\nthe main dependence for the\nbulk of transportation, both\npassencer and frelcht.\u201d\nAviation has some\nover all other forms of transpor\ntation, said Pelley. But the ele\nments of cost and\u00ab to a consider\nable extent, hazard are against,\nwidespread adoption of this mode\nof travel.\nNew equipment soon to be\nplaced in service on the New\nHaven railroad, he said, includes\nluxurious coaches with roller\nbearings which win be operated\nwithout extra fare: new Pullman\nequipment including S 3 of the\nlatest model cars, as well as\nfreight and mail cars.\nPelley said that although ra\u2019\u2019\nroads have been losing passenge.\nbusiness, he believed that it was\nnow as poor as it can be. He\nreported that In December, a\nmonth in which all business was\nslack, earnings of passenger trains\non the New Haven showed an in\ncrease.\nHe stated that in his opinion\nthe only justification for a trans\nportation system is the service\nit can render. If a waterway de\nvelopment would render such\nservice, it could be made to pay\nits own way and therefore be\ndeveloped by private capital, he\nsaid.\nThe matter of consolidation of\nNew England railroads is now\nbeing discussed by a committee\nappointed by governors of the six\nStates, and Pelley said that any\ncomment from him would be pre\nmature.\nWABASFVOTES\nSI Q DI VIDEND\nNEW YORK, Jan. 10 (IJJH.Iz-\nDirectors of the Wabash rail\nway yesterday declared a dividend\nof $5 a share on the preferred\nclass B stock for each of the years\n1928 and 1929, a total of $lO a\nshare. Dividends are payable to\nholders of record on December 31,\n1928, and January 21, re\nspectively.\nPayment of the first dividend\nwas suspended under a decision\nof the United States Circuit Court\nof Appeals, but its reversal by\nthe Surpreme Court'cleared the\nroad for payment.\nRegular quarterly dividend of\n$1.25 a share was also declared\non the preferred class A stock.\nPRODUCE SHIPMENTS\nC*r-lot zhlpmonte reported for the\nentire United State* for Wednesday,\nJanuary 8:\nApple*\u2014ldaho, Hr New York. M;\nVirginia, 40; Washington, 108; West\nVirgin!* I; other* 20. Total, 114.\nLettuce\u2014Arizona, 93; California, 94;\nFlorida. 3. Total, 189.\nOnions \u2014Colorado. 39; Indian* 25;\nMichigan, 30; New York, 11; Ohio, 1;\nothei* 20. Total, 116.\nOranges\u2014Arizona, 2; California, 100;\nFlorida, 164; Louisian* 8. Total, 869.\nPotatoes\u2014Colorado, 89; Idaho, 94;\nMaine, 347; Michigan. S 3; New York.\n25; other* 179. Total, 619.\nI timely tips\nM\u00bbn\u00aby to Loan on AatomobUo*\nLOANS PROCURED ON AUTOS\u2014\nQuick, confidential servic*.\nPortonalt\nADVICE on legal matter* tasnlly\naffairs: correspondence handled; pa\npers examined.\nUnfurnuhod Apartmant*\nKENYON ST. N. W.\u2014Desirable\nsecond floor apartment, three room*\nkitchenette and bath: very reasan\nable: Including gas and electricity.\nBosfnoM Opportmutia*\nFOR SALE\u2014Store, stock and fix\ntures; first-class business; have to\nsell on account of stokness.\nAutomobile* for Sal*\nCHEVROLET\u2014 Coach. IMS; 8825;\nterms.\nHou*** and E*ttiW for Sal*,\nD. of C.\nt DON\u2019T FAIL to MA new brick\nhouse at Holly St. N. W. Sunday;\nthe beat buy In Sixteenth Street\nHeights upder 815.000.\nFurni*h*d Apartment*\n10TH ST. N. E\u2014New buUdlng.\nFrigidatre; two room* kitchen, di\nnette; shower bath; 870 month.\nHoiue* for Rent, Unfurnished,\nD. of C.\nBTH ST. N. W.\u2014 house;\na. m. 1.: 14th Street car line; rea\nsonable.\nBoard and Room\nPARK 'BD.' N. W.\u2014Cosy room,\nwith porch: suitable one or two:\nhome-cooked\u2019 meals.\nMotorcycle* an